text: Steﬃmycin  F,  a  new  steﬃmycin-type  derivative  from  the  lichen-derived  actinomycetes  steptomyces  sp.  Chun-Yu Liu, Yue-Lan Li, Jing-Hui Lu, Li-Lin Qian, Ke Xu, Ning-Ning Wang,  ∗ Wen-Qiang Chang, Hong-Xiang Lou  Department of Natural Product Chemistry, Key Lab of Chemical Biology of Ministry of Education, School of Pharmaceutical Sciences, Shandong University,  Jinan 250012, China  Article history:  Received 29 July 2020  Revised 26 September 2020  Accepted 26 September 2020  Available online xxx  Keywords:  Actinomycetes steptomyces sp. 0630c  Steﬃmycin-type  Cytotoxicities  Antibacterial activities  Actinomycetes  are  a  kind  of  widely  distributed  gram-positive  bacteria, which are the main sources of antibiotics and other bioac-  tive natural products, including Streptomyces, Micromonospora and  Saccharopolyspora  [1] .  More  and  more  attractive  metabolites  are  discovered  from  actinomycetes  in  soils  or  oceans  [1-3] ,  such  as  peptides [ 4 , 5 ], macrolides [ 6 , 7 ], polyketide  [ 8 , 9 ], terpenoids [10] ,  alkaloid [11] , and so on. Nevertheless, the secondary metabolites  from lichen-derived actinomycetes are seldom studied [ 12 , 13 ].

Steﬃmycin was discovered from Streptomyces steﬃsburgensis as  the ﬁrst steﬃmycin-type antibiotic in 1967 [14] . So far only a few  members of the steﬃmycin family exist in the natural world, and  they generally have some antibacterial activity [14-19] . Steﬃmycin-  type, as a rare amount of antibiotic compounds, need to be fur-  ther explored. During our ongoing investigation on new cytotoxic  compounds  from  the  lichen-derived  microorganisms  [20-22] ,  so  a chemical investigation on Actinomycetes Steptomyces sp. 0630c,  inhabiting  the  lichen  Peltigera  sp.  collected  from  Zhaosu  County  of  Xinjiang  Uygur  Autonomous  Region,  China,  was  carried  out.  A  bioassay-guided  isolation  of  metabolites  from  Steptomyces  sp.  0630c  yielded  one  new  steﬃmycin-type  antibiotic  (steﬃmycin  F  ( 1 )) along with two known compounds (steﬃmycin ( 2 ) and stef-  ﬁmycin  D  ( 3 )). Cytotoxic  guided  isolation  of  the  lichen-derived  actinomycetes  Steptomyces  sp.  0630c,  yielded  a  new  steﬃmycin-type  derivative  ( 1 )  together  with  two  known  congeners  ( 2  − 3 ).  Their  structures  were  determined  based  on  comprehensive  spectroscopic  analysis  and  ECD  calculations.  It  turned  out  that  steﬃmycin-type compounds were responsible for the cytotoxic activity of the extract, in which stef-  ﬁmycin ( 2 ) was the most active one against a panel of human cancer cells MCF-7, HepG-2 and A2780  with IC 50 values of 5.05, 5.57, 1.91 μM, respectively. In addition, compounds 2 − 3 could noticeably in-  hibit the growth of Staphylococcus aureus with MIC values of 2 μg/mL.  journal homepage: www.elsevier.com/locate/molstr  Contents lists available at ScienceDirect  Journal of Molecular Structure xxx (xxxx) xxx  cidation,  plausible  biogenetic  pathway  and  bioactivities  of  these  compounds  are  described  in  detail.  Our  study  aimed  to  further  identify active and new steﬃmycin-type compounds from the sec-  ondary metabolites of actinomycetes Steptomyces sp. 0630c, which  provided basis for mining of active components of Steptomyces sp.  0630c. Simultaneously, the discovery of new compound steﬃmycin  F enriched the steﬃmycin-type compound library.  2.1. General experimental procedures

ECD calculation assay

Two conﬁgurations (7 R , 8 S , 9 S , 12 S and 7 R , 8 S , 9 S , 12 R ) were  used  as  the  model  compound  1 .  Conformational  analysis  within  an  energy  window  of  3.0  kcal/mol  was  performed  by  using  the  MMFF94 molecular mechanics force ﬁeld. The obtained conform-  ers were further optimized with the software package Gaussian 09  [23] at the B3LYP/6–31 G (2d, p) level. Then the 60 lowest elec-  tronic  transitions  were  calculated  using  time-dependent  density  functional theory (TD-DFT) methods at the B3LYP/6–31 G (d) level.  The rotational strengths of each electronic excitation were given  using both dipole length and dipole velocity representations. ECD  spectra of each conformers were simulated using a Gaussian func-  tion with a half-bandwidth of 0.20 eV. The overall theoretical ECD  spectra were then obtained according to the Boltzmann weighting  of each conformers. In the 20 0–40 0 nm region, the theoretically  calculated ECD spectra of (7 R , 8 S , 9 S , 12 S ) was in good agreement  with the experimental ECD spectra of 1 . The obtained compounds were from the cytoxic active fraction  in  the  bioassay-guided fraction  of  Steptomyces  sp.  0630c  by  em-  ploying MTT method [20] . All the compounds 1 − 3 were eval-  uated for the cytotoxicity against human cancer cells MCF-7 (hu-  man breast adenocarcinoma cell line), HepG-2 (human liver hepa-  tocellular carcinoma) and A2780 (human ovarian carcinoma). Com-  pound 2 exhibited signiﬁcant cytotoxic activity and had IC  50  val-  ues of 5.05 μM for MCF-7, 5.57 μM for HepG-2, and 1.91 μM for  A2780, respectively while compounds 1 and 3 showed weak cyto-  toxic  activity  ( Table  3 ).  In  addition,  the  compounds  1  − 3  were  tested  for  their  antibacterial  activities  against  Staphylococcus  au-  reus and E. coli using the micro-broth dilution method [24] with  vancomycin and gentamicin as positive controls, respectively. The  results ( Table 3 ) showed that compounds 2 − 3 exhibited potent  against S. aureus with MIC value of 2 μg/mL, and they were inac-  tive against E. coli .  It was reported that presteﬃmycione was the key biosynthetic  intermediate of steﬃmycin [ 28 , 29 ], which was generated by one  acetate-CoA and nine malonate-CoA through a series of enzymatic  reactions, and then steﬃmycin was eventually formed after glyco-  sylation with. Therefore, we guess that the other two steﬃmycin-  type compounds obtained in this study, including the new com-  Antibacterial activities (MIC: μg/mL)  Journal of Molecular Structure xxx (xxxx) xxx  [m5G; October 13, 2020;4:3 ]  C.-Y. pound steﬃmycin F ( 1 ) and the known steﬃmycin D ( 3 ), are prod-  ucts formed by the post-modiﬁcation of compound steﬃmycin ( 2 ).  Steﬃmycin F ( 1 ) may be formed by steﬃmycin through enzymatic  reaction with phenylacetate [30] and further decarboxylation reac-  tion, while steﬃmycin D ( 3 ) may be yielded by steﬃmycin through  a reduction ( Fig. 4 ).  In summary, steﬃmycin-type compounds are abundant in the  secondary metabolites of the lichen-derived actinomycetes Stepto-  myces sp. 0630c, where one new steﬃmycin-type compound, stef-  ﬁmycin F ( 1 ) along with two known compounds, steﬃmycin ( 2 )  and  steﬃmycin  D  ( 3 )  were  isolated,  according  to  the  bioassay-  guided separation method and the absolute conﬁguration of stef-  ﬁmycin  F  ( 1 )  was  determined  by  calculated  electronic  circular  dichroism  (ECD).  The  preliminary  bio-tests  showed  that  these  compounds could inhibit human cancer cells MCF-7, HepG-2 and  A2780 and have antibacterial activities against with the growth of  Staphylococcus aureus . We proposed the possible biosynthetic path-  way of steﬃmycin F, which further indicated its absolute ﬁguration  and the direction in explaining the metabolic relationship between  steﬃmycin F and host Steptomyces sp. 0630c, and laid the founda-  tion for the further development and utilization of steﬃmycin-type  compounds.  I  hereby  declare  that  the  manuscript  “Steﬃmycin  F,  a  new  steﬃmycin-type derivative from the lichen-derived actinomycetes  Steptomyces sp. ”submitted to Journal of Molecular Structure is true  and reliable and free from academic misconduct.
